{"key":"processedPost-11325350","value":{"id":11325350,"first":11324234,"last":11336909,"when":1256593299,"utime":"10/27/09 12:41 AM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>bangstock said:</strong><br /><a href=\"/forums/files/09-44/659010389-fc3.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/09-44/659010389-thumb_fc3.jpg\"></a></blockquote><br />You need to get it up off the floor for two reasons.&nbsp; First is that air is supposed to enter from the bottom, and pass through the perlite to the top, thus collecting moisture.&nbsp; A shotgun terrarium should always be elevated on jars, cans, bricks, etc., so that air can circulate and enter/exit from all six sides.&nbsp; The second reason for getting it up is that over 90% of the contaminant spores in a room are hovering within 1 foot of the floor.&nbsp; You should move the terrarium to a desk or table, and then elevate it above that.<br />I've never seen condensation in a shotgun terrarium.&nbsp; The holes provide enough air exchange that the temperature remains near equal on each side.<br />RR"}}